To improve performance, reduce load on your database, and provide a better user experience, implement a caching strategy. Here are some suggestions:

    In-memory caching: Cache frequently accessed data in memory using a caching library, such as Redis or Memcached. This can be particularly useful for caching network status, token details, and address balances. (Done)

    HTTP caching: Use HTTP caching headers, such as ETag and Cache-Control, to instruct clients to cache API responses. This can help reduce the load on your server and improve response times for clients.

    Pre-fetching and background jobs: Pre-fetch data for commonly accessed items, such as the latest blocks and transactions, and store them in the cache. Use background jobs to keep this data up-to-date without affecting the performance of your main application.

    (not done from here) 
    
    Database-level caching: Enable caching at the database level using features provided by your database management system. For example, PostgreSQL supports various caching mechanisms like query plan caching and shared buffers.

    Cache eviction policies: Implement cache eviction policies, such as Least Recently Used (LRU) or Time-To-Live (TTL), to manage the limited cache space efficiently and ensure that the most relevant data is kept in the cache.

When implementing a caching strategy, consider the trade-offs between freshness and performance. In a blockchain explorer, some data, like network status and mempool information, needs to be up-to-date, while other data, like historical blocks and transactions, can tolerate some latency.